1. Assume that there exists a set A with the property $T(4,p)$, $p∈{0,1,2,3,4}$, and discuss by cases: 
2. When $p=0$, the only element in A with a dot product of 0 is $(0,0,0,0)$, which contradicts that A has 4 elements;
3. When $p=1$, take the unit vector group, the dot product of different elements is 0≠1, which is a contradiction;
4. When $p=2$, the elements meeting the conditions are four-tuples with two 1s each, at most 3 of such elements satisfy that the dot product of different elements is 1, and 4 cannot be taken, which is a contradiction;
5. When $p=3$, take the four-tuples with three 1s, the dot product of different elements is 2≠1, which is a contradiction;
6. When $p=4$, the only element in A can be $(1,1,1,1)$, which contradicts that A has 4 elements;
7. In summary, there is no set A with the property $T(4,p)$.

1. Denote $c_{j}=t_{1 j}+t_{2 j}+\dots+t_{n j}(j=1,2,\dots,n)$, then $c_1+c_2+\dots+c_n=np$, and it is easy to know that $p≥2$;
2. Assume that there exists j such that $c_j≥p+1$, let j=1 for convenience, that is $c_1≥p+1$;
3. When $c_1=n$, $c_j=0$ or 1 (j≥2), at this time the total number of 1s in the elements of A is at most $2n-1<np(p≥2)$, which is a contradiction;
4. When $p+1≤c_1<n$, let the first component of the first p+1 elements be 1 and the first component of the nth element be 0. From $\alpha_n·\alpha_n=p$, it is known that $\alpha_n$ has p 1s, let its 2nd to p+1th components be 1 for convenience;
5. From the dot product of different elements being 1, each column in the 2nd to p+1th components of the first p+1 elements has at most one 1, and the number of 1s in this part is at most p. Adding p+1 1s in the first column, the total is $2p+1$;
6. Moreover, from $\alpha_i·\alpha_n=1(i≤p+1)$, each column in the 2nd to p+1th components of the first p+1 elements has at least one 1, and the number of 1s in this part is $p+1$. Adding p+1 1s in the first column, the total is $2p+2$, which is a contradiction;
7. Therefore, $c_j≤p$. Combined with $c_1+c_2+\dots+c_n=np$, we get $c_j=p(j=1,2,\dots,n)$, that is $t_{1 j}+t_{2 j}+\dots+t_{n j}=p$.
